<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDDFFE9FF29FC8A418D1A53" bold="true" box="[158,220,790,813]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">Note:</emphasis>
This species corresponds to the OTU ‘LONCHO’ of 
<bibRefCitation id="EA4E54B0FFDDFFE9FF29FCAA40221A33" author="HEBERT, P. D. N. &amp; PENTON, E. H. &amp; BURNS, J. M. &amp; JANZEN, D. H. &amp; HALLWACHS, W." box="[158,371,822,845]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" pagination="14812 - 14817" part="101" refId="ref5956" refString="HEBERT, P. D. N., PENTON, E. H., BURNS, J. M., JANZEN, D. H. &amp; HALLWACHS, W. 2004. Ten species in one: DNA barcoding reveals cryptic species in the neotropical skipper butterfly Astraptes fulgerator. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA 101, 14812 - 14817." title="Ten species in one: DNA barcoding reveals cryptic species in the neotropical skipper butterfly Astraptes fulgerator" type="journal article" year="2004">
Hebert 
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDDFFE9FF5AFCAA40721A33" box="[237,291,822,845]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">et al.</emphasis>
(2004)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C6C57ACAFFDDFFE9FF29FCCA40FD1AD2" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8E602941FFDDFFE9FF29FCCA40FD1AD2" blockId="3.[158,780,503,1227]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDDFFE9FF29FCCA404C1A13" bold="true" box="[158,285,854,877]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName id="49DF52C2FFDDFFE9FE20FCCA43511A13" authorityName="BROWER" authorityYear="2010" box="[407,512,854,877]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Astraptes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viracocha">
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDDFFE9FE20FCCA43511A13" box="[407,512,854,877]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">viracocha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a noun in apposition, is the name of a bearded white god of the Incas. The species is named for Dan Janzen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C6C57ACAFFDDFFE9FF0FFC29402C1DB5" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8E602941FFDDFFE9FF0FFC29402C1DB5" blockId="3.[158,780,503,1227]" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">
The phenetic cluster ‘NUMT’ of 
<bibRefCitation id="EA4E54B0FFDDFFE9FD99FC29425A1AB2" author="HEBERT, P. D. N. &amp; PENTON, E. H. &amp; BURNS, J. M. &amp; JANZEN, D. H. &amp; HALLWACHS, W." box="[558,779,949,972]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" pagination="14812 - 14817" part="101" refId="ref5956" refString="HEBERT, P. D. N., PENTON, E. H., BURNS, J. M., JANZEN, D. H. &amp; HALLWACHS, W. 2004. Ten species in one: DNA barcoding reveals cryptic species in the neotropical skipper butterfly Astraptes fulgerator. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA 101, 14812 - 14817." title="Ten species in one: DNA barcoding reveals cryptic species in the neotropical skipper butterfly Astraptes fulgerator" type="journal article" year="2004">
Hebert 
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDDFFE9FD36FC2943EA1AB2" box="[641,699,949,972]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">et al.</emphasis>
(2004)
</bibRefCitation>
differs from the named 
<taxonomicName id="49DF52C2FFDDFFE9FE12FC4943591A92" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1819" box="[421,520,981,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Astraptes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDDFFE9FE12FC4943591A92" box="[421,520,981,1004]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">Astraptes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species above by more character states than most of the latter differ from one another (
<bibRefCitation id="EA4E54B0FFDDFFE9FF55FB8940291D52" author="BROWER, A. V. Z." box="[226,376,1045,1068]" journalOrPublisher="Systematics and Biodiversity" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" pagination="127 - 132" part="4" refId="ref5260" refString="BROWER, A. V. Z. 2006. Problems with DNA barcodes for species delimitation: ' ten species' of Astraptes fulgerator reassessed (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 4, 127 - 132." title="Problems with DNA barcodes for species delimitation: ' ten species' of Astraptes fulgerator reassessed (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae)" type="journal article" year="2006">Brower, 2006</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EA4E54B0FFDDFFE9FE3DFB89430D1D52" author="HEBERT, P. D. N. &amp; PENTON, E. H. &amp; BURNS, J. M. &amp; JANZEN, D. H. &amp; HALLWACHS, W." box="[394,604,1045,1068]" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" pagination="14812 - 14817" part="101" refId="ref5956" refString="HEBERT, P. D. N., PENTON, E. H., BURNS, J. M., JANZEN, D. H. &amp; HALLWACHS, W. 2004. Ten species in one: DNA barcoding reveals cryptic species in the neotropical skipper butterfly Astraptes fulgerator. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA 101, 14812 - 14817." title="Ten species in one: DNA barcoding reveals cryptic species in the neotropical skipper butterfly Astraptes fulgerator" type="journal article" year="2004">
Hebert 
<emphasis id="BCABF553FFDDFFE9FE6DFB8943411D52" box="[474,528,1045,1068]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="488">et al.</emphasis>
(2004)
</bibRefCitation>
dismissed those sequences as nuclear pseudogenes, an explanation 
<bibRefCitation id="EA4E54B0FFDDFFE9FD09FBA941B51D12" author="BROWER, A. V. Z." journalOrPublisher="Systematics and Biodiversity" pageId="3" pageNumber="488" pagination="127 - 132" part="4" refId="ref5260" refString="BROWER, A. V. Z. 2006. Problems with DNA barcodes for species delimitation: ' ten species' of Astraptes fulgerator reassessed (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae). Systematics and Biodiversity 4, 127 - 132." title="Problems with DNA barcodes for species delimitation: ' ten species' of Astraptes fulgerator reassessed (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae)" type="journal article" year="2006">Brower (2006)</bibRefCitation>
showed to be extremely unlikely. Nevertheless, since the butterflies bearing these sequences have not been identified as a taxon by their discoverers, I refrain from applying a name to them here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
